The pysan library has a number of different modules which each can each be used to address specific questions in the sequence domain. The currently available modules within pysan are;

  • elements
  • subsequences
  • ngrams
  • transitions
  • spells
  • statistics

And for multisequence analysis;

  • attributes
  • derivatives
  • editdistances
  • nonalignment

To get started using the methods in these modules, the simplest way is to import all of the methods from it, and start writing;

{% raw %} 
from pysan.elements import *

sequence = [3, 2, 3, 1, 1, 3, 1, 1, 2, 3, 1, 3, 1, 3, 2, 2, 3, 1, 3, 2]
get_alphabet(sequence)

{1, 2, 3}
{% endraw %}

Alternatively, you can import just the method you need from the module like this;

{% raw %} 
from pysan.elements import get_alphabet

sequence = [3, 2, 3, 1, 1, 3, 1, 1, 2, 3, 1, 3, 1, 3, 2, 2, 3, 1, 3, 2]
get_alphabet(sequence)

{1, 2, 3}
{% endraw %}

There are also two generic modules called core and multi, which contain the basic plotting functionality described in the overview pages;

{% raw %} 
from pysan.core import plot_sequence
sequence = [1,1,2,1,2,2,3,1,1,2,2,1,2,2,3,1,1,2]
plt = plot_sequence(sequence)
plt.show()
{% endraw %}

And the multi module;

{% raw %} 
from pysan.multi import plot_sequences
s1 = [1,1,1,2,2,3,2,4,4,3,2,1,2,3,3,3,2,2,1,1,1]
s2 = [1,1,2,2,3,2,4,4,3,2,1,2,3,2,2,2,3,3,2,4,4]
s3 = [1,1,1,2,2,3,2,4,4,3,2,1,2,3,3,3,4,4,4,3,3]
s4 = [1,1,1,1,2,3,2,3,3,3,3,1,2,2,3,3,3,4,4,4,4]
sequences = [s1,s2,s3,s4]
plt = plot_sequences(sequences)
plt.show()
{% endraw %}
